<DOC><DOCNO> AP901024-0050 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-10-24-90 0556EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-Deaths     10-24 0336</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Deaths,0400</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><HEAD>Zephania Mothopeng</HEAD><DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Zephania Mothopeng, who brokeaway from the African National Congress to help form South Africa'smuch more militant Pan Africanist Congress, died Tuesday at age 77.   Mothopeng had suffered from cancer and pneumonia.   Like African National Congress leader Nelson Mandela, Mothopengspent years in prison for his political activities and was widelyrecognized in South Africa as a symbol of the black population'sstruggle against apartheid.   But unlike Mandela and other ANC leaders, Mothopeng opposednegotiating with the white-led government. Unhappy with the ANC'sefforts to work with non-blacks, he and others formed the PanAfricanist Congress in 1959.   He was serving a 15-year sentence on terrorism charges when hewas freed three years early in 1988 after being diagnosed withcancer.</TEXT><HEAD>Louis Althusser</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Louis Althusser, one of Europe's most prominentMarxist philosophers, died Monday at age 72. The cause of death wasnot disclosed.   He was already well known in 1980 when he strangled his wife atthe Ecole Normale Superieur, where he taught. He was judgedincompetent to stand trial and hospitalized at a psychiatricfacility, from which he was released in 1984.   Althusser was known for his provocative interpretations of theworks of Karl Marx, Sigmund Freud and Mao Tse-tung. His booksincluded ``For Marx,'' published in 1965, and ``Lenin andPhilosophy,'' in 1969.</TEXT><HEAD>Barney Nagler</HEAD><DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Barney Nagler, a sportswriter, TV producerand columnist for The Daily Racing Form, died Monday of arespiratory infection. He was 78.   For the past 40 years, Nagler's column, ``On Second Thought,''had appeared in The Daily Racing Form.   He also was a television producer and writer for ABC and NBC,and is credited with naming ABC's ``Wide World of Sports.''   He wrote biographies of jockey Willie Shoemaker and boxer JoeLouis.</TEXT><HEAD>Dora Baker Kelley</HEAD><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dora Baker Kelley, a World War I veteran of theArmy Nurse Corps, died Monday at age 102.   Mrs. Kelley served in the Corps in 1918-19 before going to workfor a hospital in Temple. Later she worked at VeteransAdministration hospitals in Detroit and Muskogee, Okla., and athospitals in Dallas. She retired at 79.</TEXT><TEXT/></DOC>